### PHP Associative Arrays

Associative arrays use named keys that you assign to values.

### Creating Associative Arrays

```php
<?php
// Method 1
$person = [
    "name" => "John",
    "age" => 30,
    "city" => "New York"
];

// Method 2
$person["name"] = "John";
$person["age"] = 30;
$person["city"] = "New York";
?>
```

### Accessing Elements

```php
<?php
$student = [
    "first_name" => "Alice",
    "last_name" => "Johnson",
    "grade" => 92,
    "active" => true
];

echo $student["first_name"]; // Alice
echo $student["grade"];      // 92

// Loop through
foreach ($student as $key => $value) {
    echo "$key: $value<br>";
}
?>
```

### Common Operations

| Operation | Code |
|-----------|------|
| Check key exists | `array_key_exists("key", $arr)` |
| Get all keys | `array_keys($arr)` |
| Get all values | `array_values($arr)` |
| Remove by key | `unset($arr["key"])` |
| Check value exists | `in_array($value, $arr)` |

> **Key Point:** Associative arrays are ideal for representing structured data like records or settings where meaningful keys improve code readability.
